Koil Tampur      n.       The following note is extracted
from the Travancore Census Report, 1901. The Koil Tampur      ns form a
small community, made up of the descendants of the immigrant Kshatriya
families from certain parts of Malabar lying to the north of Travancore
and Cochin. They are also known as Koil Pantalas. In early records, the
term Koviladhik      rikal appears to have been used. Immemorial
tradition connects the Koil Tampur      ns with Ch      ram      n
Perum      l, and goes to say that their original settlement was
Beypore. About 300 M.E. a few male members were invited to settle in
Travancore, and form marital alliances with the ladies of the
Travancore Royal House, known then as the V      n      t
Svar      pam. Houses were built for them at Kilim      n      r, six
miles from Attingal, where all the female members of the Royal Family
resided. In M.E. 963, eight persons       three males and five
females       from the family of       liakk      tu, oppressed by the
invasion of T      p       Sultan, sought shelter in Travancore.
Mahar      ja R      ma Varma received them kindly, and gave them the
palace of the Tekkumk      r R      ja, who had been subjugated by
R      ma Iyen Dalawah. This site in Changanachery is still recognised
as N      r      zhikkott      ram. In 975 M.E. one of the five ladies
removed to Kirtipuram near Kantiy      r [<a id=
"pb297" href="#pb297" name="pb297">297](Mavelikara
t      luk), and thence to a village called Gr      mam in the same
t      luk. Another shifted to Pallam in the Kottayam t      luk, a
third to Pa      liyakkara in Tiruvalla, and a fourth, having no issue,
continued to live at Changanachery with the fifth lady who was the
youngest in the family. Ra      ja Ra      ja Varma Koil
Tampura      n, who married Ra      ni Lakshmi Bai, sovereign of
Travancore from 985 to 990 M.E. was the eldest son of the lady that
stayed at Changanachery. Their present house at that place, known as
Lakshmipuram Kotta      ram, was named after the Koil
Tampur      n       s royal consort. R      ja R      ja Varma       s
sister gave birth to three daughters and two sons. The eldest daughter
and sons removed to Kartikapalli in 1040, and thence, in 1046, to
Anantapuram in Haripad. In 1041, the second daughter and issue removed
to Chempr      l in Tiruvalla, while the third continued to live at
Changanachery. Thus there came into existence seven families of Koil
Tampur      ns, namely those of Kilim      n      r, Changanachery,
Anantapuram, Pallam, Chempr      l, Gr      mam, and P      liyakkare.
Some time after 1040 M.E. (A.D. 1856), three more families, viz., those
of Cheruk      l, K      r      mma, and Vatakk      matham, immigrated
from North Malabar.
The Koil Tampur      ns are all regarded as blood relations, and
observe birth and death pollutions like D      y      dis among
Br      hmans. They follow the matriarchal system of inheritance.
Namb      tiri Br      hmans marry their ladies. Their religious
ceremonies are the same as those of Namb      tiris, whom they resemble
in the matter of food and drink. Their caste government is in the hands
of the Namb      tiri Vaidikans.
Their ceremonies are the usual Br      hmanical
Samsk      ras       G      takarma, N      makarana, Annapr      sana,
etc. Regarding the N      makarana, or naming, the only <span class=
"pagenum">[<a id="pb298" href="#pb298" name=
"pb298">298]noteworthy fact is that the first-born male
always goes by the name of R      ja R      ja Varma. The
Upan      yana, or investiture with the sacred thread, takes place in
the sixteenth year of age. On the morning of the Upan      yana, Chaula
or the tonsure ceremony is performed. It is formally done by the
Namb      tiri priest in the capacity of Guru, just as the father does
to his son among Br      hmans, and afterwards left to be completed by
the M      r      n. The priest invests the boy with the thread, and,
with the sacrificial fire as lord and witness, initiates him in the
G      yatri prayer. The Koil Tampur      ns are to repeat this prayer
morning, noon and evening, like the Br      hmans, but are to do so
only ten times on each occasion. On the fourth day, the boy listens to
a few V      dic hymns recited by the priest. There is not the
prolonged course of severe discipline of the Br      hmanical
Brahmach      ri, which the Namb      tiris so religiously observe. The
Sam      vartana, or pupilage stage, is performed on the fifteenth day.
The ceremony of proceeding to Benares is then gone through. Just as in
the case of the Br      hmans, a would-be father-in-law intercedes, and
requests the Sn      taka (past Brahmach      ri) to bless his
daughter, and settle in life as a Grihastha. The Namb      tiri priest
then steps in to remind the boy of his dharma (duty) as a Kshatriya,
and gives him a sword symbolic of his pre-ordained function in
society.
The marriage of a Koil Tampur      n does not present many peculiar
features. One item in the programme, called D      kshavirippu, may be
referred to. During all the four days of the marriage, the bride is
confined to a special room, where a white cloth with a carpet over it
is spread on the floor, and a lamp burns day and night. The ceremonial
bridegroom is either an Aryappattar or a Namb      tiri, now generally
a Namb      tiri. Of course, [<a id="pb299" href=
"#pb299" name="pb299">299]the marriage is a mere ceremonial,
and the bridegroom at the ceremony is not necessarily the spouse of
actual life. His death deprives her of the right to wear the t      li,
and makes her an Amangali (an inauspicious person) for all
socio-religious purposes. At sr      ddhas (memorial service for the
dead), the Tampur      tti with her married husband alive faces the
east, and one that has lost him has to look in the direction of
Yamal      ka (south).
Mr. Ravi Varma, the celebrated artist, who died recently, was a Koil
